{"ts":"2026-06-26T17:10:00.493Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Reviewing Input Flow**\n\nI'm pleased to report that the linting check has successfully passed without any reported issues. Now, I'm shifting focus to thoroughly review the design goals and requirements for the blueprint generator wizard input flow. This includes scoping the phase3-tool, targeting the /build/blueprint input flow and understanding task requirements to upgrade /build/blueprint.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T17:10:02.514Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining Wizard Steps**\n\nI'm now diving deep into the individual steps of the blueprint wizard. I've mapped out the planned steps: organization (with optional budget and geography considerations), priorities (max 3), AI journey, data and leadership, and the crucial challenge input. A key hurdle is the challenge step, which needs to be a text area as per the requirement, but the old system uses a select. I'm exploring interactive options that marry text input with the existing selection-based logic to maintain compatibility.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T17:10:03.443Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Clarifying Requirement Scope**\n\nI've re-read the requirements carefully and am clarifying the wizard step scope. Step 1 will encompass organization details: industry, company size (both required), with optional budget and geography fields. Step 2 will focus on priorities, limited to a selection of up to three. Step 3 is dedicated to the AI journey stage. The challenge field will be a text area. I am currently focused on organizing the structure and design before focusing on rendering to the screen.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T17:10:05.228Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Mapping Challenge Solutions**\n\nI've finalized step 4, encompassing data readiness and leadership commitment. Now, I'm grappling with step 5, the challenge input. There's a connection to `getRecommendedSolution(challenge)`, and I've got to find a way to map user-entered custom text to a recommended solution. My current plan is to introduce stylish quick-tag buttons for common challenges like \"Legacy Systems\" and \"Skill Shortages,\" which can pre-populate or map to the underlying keys.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T17:10:07.130Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Matching Challenge Inputs**\n\nI'm now refining the challenge input step, and I've developed a sophisticated approach. I'm leveraging both a premium text area for free-form input and interactive quick-tag buttons for common challenges. I'll analyze the user's text for keywords to categorize the challenge. If the input mentions \"tech,\" \"legacy,\" or \"database,\" I will assign the \"Tech Stack\" tag. Keywords such as \"budget,\" \"cost,\" or \"roi\" will map to \"Budget/ROI.\" If the keywords are \"talent,\" \"skill,\" or \"hire\" it will be categorized as \"Talent Shortage.\" Likewise, if keywords like \"security,\" \"compliance,\" or \"privacy\" are found, the tag will be \"Security/Compliance.\" Otherwise, a fallback to \"Change Management\" is assigned.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T17:10:08.544Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Validating User Input**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the challenge input step validation. I will ensure the text area for the challenge requires a minimum length, specifically ensuring that users enter at least 10 characters to improve the robustness of the system. I will add quick tag buttons for commonly classified challenges like \"AI talent\", \"Security/Compliance\", and \"Organizational resistance\" in order to classify the challenge for the GFF calculation engine while still keeping the narrative custom and premium. Also, I am verifying how to integrate email and OTP step as Step 6.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T17:10:10.316Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Defining Design Scope**\n\nI've got the six-step flow, and it's looking clean! I'm now detailing the design plan, keeping UI quality and task guidelines front-of-mind. The tool is for enterprise buyers, and the aim is for a premium, interactive feel, like a McKinsey or Gartner tool. The flow: structural questions to strategic alignment to detailing operational roadblocks to securing a report. I am envisioning a sovereign command deck / tactical radar HUD as the visual metaphor.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T17:10:12.352Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Visualizing Interactive Elements**\n\nI'm now outlining the UI for the wizard, and I'm quite excited about it. I'm focusing on a top progress rail, custom cards with interactive radio options, and a premium text area for the challenge step with a character count and glow. Also, I'm thinking of an \"Assessment Completeness Map\". Step 6 will have an expensive-looking OTP validation. The layout will be centered with a responsive 2-column or 1-column layout, featuring dark glassmorphism styling.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
