{"ts":"2026-06-26T17:10:57.436Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Pinpointing Usage**\n\nOkay, so I've confirmed that `BuildAIEnterpriseSection` basically just wraps the `<BlueprintGenerator />` component. It seems the only place that happens is on the LandingPage, specifically within the `#blueprint` section. That means any change or development will flow from there. I'll focus on that component now.\n\n\n**Focusing on Requirements**\n\nI'm now fully immersed in the project requirements. I've re-read the multi-step wizard build, making sure I haven't missed any details. The requirement to avoid impacting the landing page's existing blueprint generation and scoring is clear, and I'm designing accordingly, especially on the `BlueprintGenerator` component. Preserving the existing homepage logic is also a priority.\n\n\n**Designing the Wizard**\n\nMy focus is now on meticulously designing the multi-step wizard, keeping the \"do not modify landing page\" rule firmly in mind. This upgrade will replace the existing, simpler version of the `BlueprintGenerator` component. It's crucial to ensure the existing homepage blueprint generation, scoring rules, layout, and component mounting remain intact. I'm exploring the options within `lib/blueprint-data.ts`, particularly the `industryOptions`, to inform the wizard's steps.\n\n\n**Defining Selection Options**\n\nI've been exploring the various option sets that can inform the wizard's selections. There's company size, priority, AI journey stage, data readiness, leadership buy-in, key challenges, budget, and geography. Each set is critical to tailoring the wizard's recommendations. Now I'm shifting from just identifying options to figuring out the ideal way to display them. I'm keen to make the user experience visually engaging and intuitive.\n\n\n**Crafting Interface Details**\n\nI'm now fully immersed in the UI/UX design for the wizard's interactive elements. I'm focusing on clean, premium-designed buttons with custom select mechanisms, aiming for a luxurious and responsive feel. A step-by-step layout is being crafted, complete with a glowing progress rail and distinct step numbers. I am designing a live-updating summary panel, so users see the selected parameters compile real-time. This dynamic panel will compile \"Current Organization Parameters.\" This builds a highly visual and interactive experience. I also am thinking through the validation logic, considering error warnings and red text glow effects. I'm also including a high-fidelity text area for Step 5, which will map keywords from the user's challenge to backend solutions.\n\n\n**Analyzing Challenge Mapping**\n\nI've been thinking about Step 5, the challenge input field. The goal is to dynamically map the user's free text to pre-defined challenge keys. I'm exploring how keyword analysis can help, by storing the entered text and cross-referencing it to existing keys like \"Tech Stack\" or \"Budget/ROI.\" Then, I'll leverage the `getRecommendedSolution` function, by passing in the mapped key. This allows us to provide a highly tailored solution, so this will be a good UI experience. I'm now writing a helper function for the mapping process.\n\n\n**Refining Keyword Mapping**\n\nI'm refining my keyword mapping function for the challenge input. I've added more categories, like \"Data Security\" and \"Internal Buy-In,\" with a more exhaustive list of associated keywords. The function's logic is now more robust. This is so that the wizard can accurately categorize user input and improve the recommendation accuracy, which will improve the user experience.\n\n\n\n**Implementing Dual Input**\n\nI've decided to implement a dual-input method for the challenge step! Users will now select a main challenge category from visually appealing icon cards (like \"Security & Compliance,\" \"Legacy Tech\"), and then provide more detail in a text area. This combines structured selection for accurate scoring with free-form input for a personalized feel. This feels perfect! I'm now implementing this and testing.\n\n\n**Mapping State Logic**\n\nOkay, I've confirmed that the `BlueprintAnswers` interface in `lib/blueprint-data.ts` perfectly maps to the wizard's state. I've broken down the required wizard steps and their exact requirements. It is a simple mapping from our state, and can proceed with implementation of these steps. I've designed logic that ensures that the required inputs are selected, and will include input validation logic.\n\n\n**Validating Inputs**\n\nI'm now fully immersed in the validation logic for each step. For Step 4, I'm ensuring both data readiness and leadership commitment are selected. Step 5 requires a challenge category selection and a minimum of 10 characters in the text area. And Step 6 will include email format validation. I am designing the logic and UI to ensure the user gets a great experience. I also need to make sure the OTP step is frontend only.\n\n\n**Refining Simulation Details**\n\nI'm now integrating the OTP simulation within the wizard's workflow, where instead of requesting an OTP code, a simulation message will provide instructions to enter any 6-digit code. Then, it will redirect to Step 7 (the interactive report!). I will make sure the report looks great.\n\n\n**Confirming Icon Implementation**\n\nI'm now focusing on integrating custom SVG icons and checking which icons we can use. I'm verifying the availability of `lucide-react` for the project and then checking for any icons currently imported. It seems that we can import these icons, or even draw custom lightweight SVGs directly in TSX. I'm choosing the method that is safest and most performant, and then I'll move on to implementing it.\n\n\n**Designing Inline SVG Icons**\n\nOkay, the plan is locked in! I'm now fully committed to implementing inline SVG icons for the wizard. After reviewing `BlueprintGenerator.tsx`, I've finalized the component breakdown, focusing on clean, modular sections to handle the wizard's logic. I'm focusing on writing out the entire `BlueprintGenerator.tsx` code. The use of custom SVGs promises a cleaner, faster, and more easily designed UI.\n\n\n**Designing Sidebar Display**\n\nI'm now fully immersed in designing the dynamic synthesis sidebar. It'll show a live \"Topology Blueprinting\" status with a pulsing dot. Each completed field will then \"light up,\" providing a clear visual representation of the user's progress: industry, company size, priorities, AI maturity, data readiness, and challenge details. It's a masterclass in premium enterprise UX!\n\n\n**Crafting Dynamic Selections**\n\nI'm now laser-focused on designing the custom selection cards, ensuring each step feels premium and intuitive. For industry, company size, and priorities, I'm designing bespoke card grids with unique micro-graphics. An AI journey progression map will guide users, and the elegant grids are planned for data readiness, leadership commitment, and challenge categories. The live updating summary panel will provide real time parameter updates.\n\n\n**Implementing Transitions**\n\nI'm now implementing the UI design for the OTP simulation, building a premium enterprise gate with an input field and lock icon. I'll add a verification card for the OTP input that slides in and features clear guidance. I'm also planning the progress rail's visual design, including glowing lines, pulsing borders for the active step, and checkmarks for completed steps. Smooth CSS transitions, especially slide-in/fade-in animations, will be key. I'll check for existing classes and create them as needed.\n\n\n\n**Implementing Animations**\n\nI'm now implementing the CSS animations in the `<BlueprintGenerator.tsx>` component. I'm using an inline `<style>` tag. I'm focusing on defining animations for smooth transitions and pulsing glows for an engaging user experience, using an inline `<style>` block. Now, I'm checking the current functions for any impact. I've confirmed that I won't affect the existing scoring calculations and reports.\n\n\n**Revising Report Generation**\n\nI'm now revising the report generation process, specifically the logic after the OTP input. I've confirmed that `isCompiling`, `reportGenerated`, and `step` variables manage the report flow. I will now adjust the code to reflect the six wizard steps, making Step 7 the dedicated report page. I'll make sure the loading screen animation and data handling are also optimized!\n\n```\n\n\n\n**Validating User Input**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the state validation logic and the flow of user input, ensuring a seamless user experience. I'm focusing on crafting specific validation rules, error handling, and navigating between steps. I've focused on clean logic and UI/UX transitions.\n\n\n**Refining Validation Rules**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the validation rules for each step, and integrating them into the existing component state. I'm prioritizing comprehensive checks for all required fields, including the challenge text, AI journey, data readiness, and leadership commitment. I will ensure error messages are clear and the navigation is seamless.\n\n\n**Confirming Wizard Integration**\n\nI'm now fully immersed in the integration of the OTP simulation within the wizard workflow. After entering the email in Step 6, the simulated OTP entry will be triggered. The process appears robust. The `verifyOtpAndGenerate` function is also clean and efficient. No modifications appear necessary beyond `BlueprintGenerator.tsx`.\n\n\n"}}
